Cambridge professors will set tough new maths A-levels after the university became the first in Britain to intervene in the exam system, amid concerns about the quality of the country's qualifications.

Its mathematicians will script new syllabuses and exam questions as part of the Government's reforms to drive up education standards, it was reported today.

Cambridge's department of pure mathematics is said to have submitted a report to the Department for Education outlining how new-style maths A-levels should be structured.

