The Government announced earlier this year that it intends to give universities, particularly the most elite institutions, a ‘far greater role’ in designing A-levels in the future.

It comes amid concerns that the qualifications are failing to prepare teenagers for degree study. But a leading higher education group has said it is against the plan.

Universities UK said it does not believe it would be ‘advisable or feasible’ for the sector to ‘take ownership’ of the qualifications.

